Problem 1 Dice Game

a

Version 1

play_dice_v1<-function(x){
  
  t=0
  for (i in 1:x){
    t=t-2#delete the cost each time
    u=sample(1:6,1)#sample each dice
    if(u==3|u==5){
      t=t+2*u
    }}
  return(t)
}
play_dice_v1(10)
[1] 10
play_dice_v1(10)
[1] 16

Version 2

play_dice_v2<-function(x){
  result_of_dice=sample(1:6,x,replace = TRUE)
  t=ifelse(result_of_dice==3|result_of_dice==5,result_of_dice*2-2,-2)
  #vectorized on list, learned from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/9449184/if-else-vs-ifelse-with-lists
  return(sum(t))
}
play_dice_v2(10)
[1] 28
play_dice_v2(10)
[1] 6

Version 3

play_dice_v3<-function(x){
  result_of_dice=sample(1:6,x,replace = TRUE)
  t=table(result_of_dice)
  res=-2*x
  if(!is.na(as.numeric(t[names(t)==5][1]))){
  res=res+as.numeric(t[names(t)==5][1])*2*5}#check there has result with 5
  if(!is.na(as.numeric(t[names(t)==3][1]))){
  res=res+as.numeric(t[names(t)==3][1])*2*3}#check there has result with 3
  return (res)
}
play_dice_v3(1)
[1] -2

Version 4

play_dice_v4<-function(x){
  result_of_dice=sample(1:6,x,replace = TRUE)
t=sapply(result_of_dice,function(a){if(a==3|a==5) a*2-2 else -2})# use a new list to represent the result of calculation
return(sum(t))
}
play_dice_v4(5)
[1] -10

e

montecarl<-function(num_sims,tries){#we separate numbers of simulation and tries here
  res=0
  for (i in 1:num_sims){
    res=res+play_dice_v2(tries)#we choose the function with the smallest running time
  }
  return(res/num_sims/tries)#get the simulated expectation of throwing one dice 
}
montecarl(100000,100)
[1] 0.66788
montecarl(100000,1)
[1] 0.67272

As shown in the simulation,It is not a fair game for both sides, the challenger has an advantage in expectation. Also, we can show it in calculation that:

\[ \begin{aligned} E(x)=&P(x\neq3 \cap x\neq5)\cdot(-2)+P(x=3)\cdot(3\cdot2-2)+P(x=5)\cdot(5\cdot2-2)\\ =&-\frac{2\cdot2}{3}+\frac{4}{6}+\frac{8}{6}=\frac{2}{3}>0 \end{aligned} \]

From the results, we can see that if we set the standard as p-value<0.05, the width, torque, and horsepower are significant in this model.

We can observe that with a higher torque, the highway mpg of the car is expected to be smaller according to the negative coefficient. If the torque increases by 1, the highway mpg is expected by 0.0507. In addition, with a higher width, the highway mpg of the car is expected to be smaller, while cars with a higher horsepower are expected to have a bigger highway mpg.
